This paper discusses bibliometric methods for evaluating scholarly impact, which is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The paper specifically mentions the use of percentile measures in evaluating scholars and institutions, which is relevant to the sub-fields of digital libraries (cs.DL) and information retrieval (cs.IR). The paper also discusses the problems of time- and field-normalization, which are relevant to the sub-fields of cybernetics (cs.CY) and social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper discusses the use of bar graphs and beamplots to present percentile ranks, which is relevant to the sub-field of cryptography (cs.CR).
